{{Notability|date=August 2009}}
The '''cognitive elite''' of a [[society]], according to [[Richard J. Herrnstein]] and [[Charles Murray (political scientist)|Charles Murray]], are those having higher [[intelligence (trait)|intelligence]] levels and thus better prospects for success in life. The development of a cognitive elite during the 20th century is presented in their 1994 book ''[[The Bell Curve]]''. In this book, Herrnstein and Murray propose that the cognitive elite has been produced by a more technological society which offers enough high skill jobs for those with a higher intelligence to fill. They also propose that by removing [[race (classification of human beings)|race]], [[gender]] or [[social class|class]] as criteria the main criteria of success in academic and professional life is becoming primarily based on cognitive ability.
[[Educational psychology|Educational psychologist]] [[Linda Gottfredson]] wrote: {{cquote|Differences in intelligence matter. For members of the cognitive elite to maintain otherwise is like the rich arguing that money does not matter. Differences in ''[[General intelligence factor|g]]'' affect the lives of individuals and families. They help shape the social order and limit our ability to reshape it.<ref>[http://www.udel.edu/educ/gottfredson/reprints/1997whygmatters.pdf Why g matters]</ref>}}
==Criticism== The [[The Bell Curve#Criticisms|book has met with criticism]], as has the cognitive elite concept.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Wilson|first1=Frank Harold|title=For Whom Does the Bell Toll?: Meritocracy, the Cognitive Elite, and the Continuing Significance of Race in Postindustrial America|quote=It refutes as cultural superstition and social science pornography The Bell Curve's theories on the role of intelligence in the social stratification of postindustrial America. It further refutes Herrnstein and Murray's ideas about the effects of IQ on social outcomes such as poverty, schooling, occupation, and underemployment, and counters the pessimistic public policy proposals their research engenders.|journal=The Journal of Negro Education|date=1995|volume=64|issue=3|pages=253|doi=10.2307/2967207|jstor=2967207}}</ref> It has been claimed that the case has been "wildly exaggerated",<ref>{{cite book|last1=Lemann|first1=Nicholas|title=Intelligence, Genes, and Success|publisher=Springer New York|isbn=9780387949864|pages=315–325|url=https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-1-4612-0669-9_14|language=en|chapter=Is There a Cognitive Elite in America?|doi=10.1007/978-1-4612-0669-9_14|quote=Therefore the cognitive elite should be understood as a sociological cartoon with political uses, not a phenomenon to be accepted at face value.}}</ref> and it is based on an [[G factor (psychometrics)#Challenges|intelligence measure that is also criticized]].
